        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4052790744" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17551900417492330341">This book begins like a narration by a stentorian voice, âThere once lived a man named Martin Dresslerâ¦â, but I see this more as some fantasy being narrated by Rod Serling. Picture yourself vision about to start a vacation which youâve fantasized about all your life and you encounter with one problem after another as you prepare to leave but you finally arrive at the airport, only to find your flight is delayed. Nevertheless, you finally board, strapped in only to have the captain announce that </span>
  <span id="freeText17551900417492330341" style="display:none">This book begins like a narration by a stentorian voice, âThere once lived a man named Martin Dresslerâ¦â, but I see this more as some fantasy being narrated by Rod Serling. Picture yourself vision about to start a vacation which youâve fantasized about all your life and you encounter with one problem after another as you prepare to leave but you finally arrive at the airport, only to find your flight is delayed. Nevertheless, you finally board, strapped in only to have the captain announce that there will be another delay because there are 87 planes in line for the only runway as the others have been damaged due to excessive seagull guano or something but be patient, the flight attendants will be passing out extra bags of peanuts to compensate for this unanticipated problem. After 90 minutes or so, there is another announcement that the airport of your destination is fogged in so to keep you amused, they will now show a bonus in-flight movie, âThe Brady Bunch Meet Draculaâ, or some such â but the projector breaks. Luckily for you, your neighbor has brought along snapshots of EVERY vacation he or she has been on before and proceeds to show them to you, accompanied by family anecdotes such as when Uncle Lester fell out of the tree or Mom burned the cookies and the fire department arrived. Soon darkness falls, passengers are snoring and you finally come to the conclusion that this flight will NEVER EVER take off â much like this book. Youâre inâ¦The Twilight Zone!!!! Why do I say this? This book has a very thin plot â wafer thin â interspersed with Martinâs dreams â but then the plot mostly runs out and youâre left with all of his remaining phantasmagorical fantasies, like one of those books of unfeasible architectural projects. The setting of an emerging New York at the end of the 19th century is interesting but this is finally âThe Winchester Mystery House Meets the Tower of Babelâ, an endless and pointless exercise in writing. <br /><br />The biggest wonder here was how this ever won the Pulitzer. The runners-up were a book of short stories by Ursula K. Le Guin, âUnlocking the Airâ, that werenât fantasy and also included unfinished drafts, and âThe Mannikinâ, by Joanna Scott, a mix of a creepy house, taxidermy and the arrival of a housekeeper who keeps the young mistress âintriguedâ, which may have been too much thrown in for some judges. I smell compromise between warring factions. The non-fiction winner, âAngelaâs Ashesâ, may have been the real quality that year but thatâs my personal opinion; obviously, there were those who were captivated by this book but to quote AbeBooks list on 10 most-forgotten Pulitzer fiction winners, this book deserves a mention because no oneâs buying it. Nor did I.<br /></span>
